SIMPLE: traduction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Traduction
<hw>Tra*duc"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>traductio</ets> a transferring: cf. F. <ets>traduction</ets>
translation. See <er>Traduce</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Transmission
from one to another.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Traditional communication and <qex>traduction</qex> of truths.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Translation from one language to another.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Derivation by descent; propagation.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If by <qex>traduction</qex> came thy mind,⟦br⟧
Our wonder is the less to find⟦br⟧
A soul so charming from a stock so good.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act of transferring; conveyance;
transportation.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>traduction</xex>
of brutes.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Transition.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>A process of reasoning in which
each conclusion applies to just such an object as each of the premises
applies to.</def> <rj><au>Jevons.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traductive</ent>⟦br⟧
